Kinrentius catuaba


sp. nov.

subSubSection.paragraph:
Diagnosis.
Male pygofer posterior margin with a long acute posterior process (PP); ventral margin with multidentate anteroventral (AVP) and posteroventral (PVP) processes, with several small dentiform projections between them (
Figs 8–10
). Aedeagus weakly constricted sub-basally; dorsal surface with short median keel at apical half; well-developed dorsal projection forming a distinct process at mid-length (
Figs 14, 15
); paired apical processes, in lateral view, each strongly expanded, with anterior margin broadly rounded, posterior margin irregularly serrated (
Fig. 16
).

Coloration
. Head yellow, with light brown irregular maculae; pair of dark brown maculae on posterior margin; coronal suture dark brown(
Figs 1, 2
). Face with frontoclypeus brown laterally and light brown medially, with irregular dark brown maculae on ventral half; gena and lorum light brown with dark brown maculae (
Fig. 3
). Pronotum and mesonotum yellow with irregular maculae and fine transverse stripes, dark brown (
Figs 1, 2
). Forewing yellow, with dark brown irregular maculae over the entire surface; costal margin brown basally (
Figs 1, 2
, 
7
).

Male genitalia.
Pygofer, in lateral view, subquadrangular, length slightly greater than height; posterodorsal angle acutely rounded; posterior margin with an internally curved acute posterior process (PP); ventral margin with two multidentate processes: posteroventral (PVP) longer than anteroventral (AVP) one, with several small dentiform projections between them (
Figs 8–10
). Style with few fine setae on preapical lobe; apex sclerotized, acuminate, curved ventrally (
Figs 12, 13
). Aedeagus weakly constricted sub-basally; lateral shelf-like area relatively long; dorsal surface with short keel at apical half; well-developed dorsal projection forming a distinct process at midlength (
Figs 14, 15
); paired apical processes, in lateral view, each strongly expanded, with anterior margin broadly rounded and posterior margin irregularly serrated (
Fig. 16
).

Diagnosis:
Male pygofer posterior margin with a long acute posterior process (PP); ventral margin with anteroventral process (AVP) long, posteroventral process (PVP) very short, tooth-like (
Figs 17–19
).Aedeagus weakly constricted sub-basally; dorsal surface with long median keel at apical half (
Figs 23, 24
); without pronounced dorsal projection at mid-length; paired apical processes, in caudal view, each subquadrate, with apical portion weakly sclerotized and apical margin approximately straight and slightly serrated (
Fig. 25
).

Male genitalia:
Pygofer in lateral view, subquadrangular, as long as tall; posterodorsal angle acutely rounded; posterior margin with a long acute posterior process (PP in 
Fig. 18
); ventral margin with two processes: anteroventral long (AVP) and posteroventral short, tooth-like, curved inwardly (PVP) (
Figs 17–19
). Style with fine and long setae on preapical lobe; apex sclerotized, acuminate, curved ventrally (
Figs 21, 22
). Aedeagus weakly constricted sub-basally; lateral shelf-like area relatively long; dorsal surface with long keel at apical half (
Figs 23, 24
); without pronounced dorsal projection at midlength; paired apical processes, in caudal view, each subquadrate, with apical portion weakly sclerotized and apical margin approximately straight and slightly serrated (
Fig 25
).

subSection.paragraph:
Here the genus is recorded for the first time in Brazil and distributional records of species show clear patterns over the Amazonian lowlands and the North-Central Moist Andes ( Fig. 26 ). However, as observed in other groups (e.g. Hall 2005 ;
Chazot et al. 2016
;
Hutter et al. 2017
) it is not clear if dispersion of species occurred from the Amazon into the Andean region or vice versa. Further investigations on the evolution of the tribe Bahitini and the subfamily Deltocephalinae are needed to clarify the group’s biogeographical history. These South American ecological systems are enormously diverse (
Borges et al . 2004
;
Mittermeier et al. 2011
), suggesting that more sampling is needed to assess the diversity of
Kinrentius
and related genera in both areas.
